46","1335–Male":"1335–Overleden","–1386":"–1386","1310–Female":"1310–Overleden","1327":"1327","1315":"1315","1335":"1335","1346":"1346","1310":"1310","1255":"1255","1386":"1386","1382":"1382","Circa 1310":"circa 1310","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Yardley, Worcestershire, England":"Yardley, Worcestershire, England","Ashworth Hall, Heywood, Lancashire, England":"Heywood, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England"},"en":{"Circa 1310–":"about 1310–Deceased","1255–1317":"1255–1317","1327–1346":"1327–1346","1335–Male":"1335–Deceased","–1386":"–1386","1310–Female":"1310–Deceased","1327":"1327","1315":"1315","1335":"1335","1346":"1346","1310":"1310","1255":"1255","1386":"1386","1382":"1382","Circa 1310":"about 1310","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Yardley, Worcestershire, England":"Yardley, Worcestershire, England","Ashworth Hall, Heywood, Lancashire, England":"Heywood, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cory","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Corey  .","Americanized form of Arabic   Khoury   or   Khouri   ‘priest’. Compare   Corey  ,   Corry  , and   Kory  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Khoury","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Arabic/Muslim Nabil, Sami, Samir, Issa, Ibrahim, Ramzi, Bassam, Fouad, Habib, Issam, Jamil, Riad.  French Michel, Antoine, Emile, Pierre, Andre, Camille, Clemence, Clovis, Georges, Gisele, Henri, Jacques.","Arabic (mainly Lebanon, Syria, and Jordan): from <i>khūrī</i> ‘priest’, in particular a Christian priest. This surname is used among Christians, including Assyrians/Chaldeans. Compare   Cory  ,   Coury  ,   Cury  ,   Elkhoury  ,   Khouri  ,   Kory  ,   Koury  , and   Kury  ."]},{"name":"Corby","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places in northern England. Those in Lincolnshire and Northamptonshire are named with the Old Norse personal name <i>Kori</i> (see   Cory  ) + Old Norse <i>býr</i> ‘farm, settlement’, whereas the one in Cumbria has as its first element the Old Irish personal name <i>Corc</i>.","French: nickname from a diminutive of <i>corb</i> ‘crow’."]},{"name":"Corey","meanings":["English: possibly from the Old Norse personal names <i>Kori</i> (of unexplained etymology) or <i>Kári</i> (from <i>kárr</i> ‘curl’ or ‘quarrelsome’). Alternatively, a habitational name from one or more of Curry Mallet or Curry Rivel (Somerset), West Curry or Cory in Morwenstow (Cornwall), or the river name in Coryton (Devon), all of which have early spellings with <i>-o-</i>.","Irish (Down; Tyrone): variant of   Curry  .","Americanized form of Arabic   Khoury   or   Khouri   ‘priest’. Compare   Cory   and   Korey  ."]}]},{"name":"Judeth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, meaning ‘Jewess’ or ‘woman from Judea’, borne by a Jewish heroine whose story is recorded in the Book of Judith in the Apocrypha. Judith is portrayed as a beautiful widow who delivers her people from the invading Assyrians by gaining the confidence of their commander, Holofernes, and cutting off his head while he is asleep; without their commander, the Assyrians are duly routed. This has been a perennially popular Jewish name. In the English-speaking world it was taken up in the 16th century, having been in occasional use among Gentiles before this: for example, it was borne by a niece of William the Conqueror. It enjoyed great popularity between the 1940s and the 1960s. Today's notable bearers include the American novelist  Judith Krantz  (  b. 1928 ) and the Scottish composer  Judith Weir  (  b. 1954 )."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":5,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":18,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705195,"age":72,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Judeth Cory Coy was born about 1310, in Lancashire, England. She had at least 3 sons with John Del Holte II."},"et":{"Circa 1310–":"umbes 1310–Surnud","1255–1317":"1255–1317","1327–1346":"1327–1346","1335–Male":"1335–Surnud","–1386":"–1386","1310–Female":"1310–Surnud","1327":"1327","1315":"1315","1335":"1335","1346":"1346","1310":"1310","1255":"1255","1386":"1386","1382":"1382","Circa 1310":"umbes 1310","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Yardley, Worcestershire, England":"Yardley, Worcestershire, England","Ashworth Hall, Heywood, Lancashire, England":"Heywood, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"Circa 1310–":"noin 1310–Kuollut","1255–1317":"1255–1317","1327–1346":"1327–1346","1335–Male":"1335–Kuollut","–1386":"–1386","1310–Female":"1310–Kuollut","1327":"1327","1315":"1315","1335":"1335","1346":"1346","1310":"1310","1255":"1255","1386":"1386","1382":"1382","Circa 1310":"noin 1310","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Yardl